body:
I propose adding a package, `encoding/form` (or possibly `encoding/url` and `encoding/multipart`, benefits to be weighed in the proposal document), that implements an HTTP `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` and `multipart/form-data` encoder and decoder with an API similar to the `encoding/json` and `encoding/xml` packages and can marshal/unmarshal forms and structs.

The primary use case I see in this would be to simplify accepting HTTP requests where the body may be a form submission or a JSON or XML encoded API request without having to leave the well-vetted comfort of the standard library. There are existing packages which implement an API similar to this eg. [`gorilla/schema`](https://godoc.org/github.com/gorilla/schema), but it seems like such a common use case and would most likely be used very often next to the JSON/XML packages, that I feel it's worth having in the standard library.

```go
// implemented by json.Decoder, xml.Decoder, and eventually by our proposed
// form decoder(s)
type InterfaceDecoder interface {
  Decode(v interface{}) error
}

// Holds the body of an incoming request
type APIBody struct {
  ID int `json:"id" form:"-"`
  XSRF `json:"-" form:"_csrf"`
  Field string `json:"somefield" form:"somefield"`
}

func HandleRequest(w ResponseWriter, r *Request) {
  var d InterfaceDecoder
  switch r.Header.Get("Content-Type") {
  case "application/json":
    d = json.NewDecoder(r.Body)
  case "application/xml", "text/xml":
    d = xml.NewDecoder(r.Body)
  case "application/x-www-form-urlencoded", "multipart/form-data":
    d = form.NewDecoder(r.Body)
  }

  data := &APIBody{}
  if err := d.Decode(data); err != nil {
    panic(err)
  }
  â€¦
}
```

I have begun working on a proposal document which will outline an exact API. This issue is to discuss the idea and see if it would be accepted in the first place and as a location for the proposal document to reference.
